  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "This reduced performance in more complex classification scenarios can be attributed to the increased difficulty in distinguishing between three sentiment categories as opposed to a simpler positive/negative dichotomy.Third, sentiment prediction accuracy correlates positively and statistically significantly with word length, as evidenced by the presence of 'Big Words', across all LLMs (p < 0.001).",
    "This phenomenon may be attributed to extensive and voluminous datasets used for LLM training, making them inherently more proficient at dealing with complex and domainspecific language.",
    "The most pronounced effect is observed in GPT-4, with a coefficient of 1.137, followed by Llama 2, and aligns with expectations, given that GPT-4 was trained on an estimated 14 trillion tokens, compared to Llama 2 with 2 trillion tokens [59,63].",
    "(Example of a movie review incl.",
    "domain-specific language that was correctly classified as negative by GPT-4 and incorrectly classified as positive by Llama 2: \"a battle between bug-eye theatre and dead-eye matinee\").Fourth, the analysis reveals that all models exhibit a decline in prediction accuracy when dealing with documents consisting of a single sentence compared to multiple sentences."
  ],
